library("orthopolynom")

compare = function(..., variables = list()) {
	metric = function (vs) do.call(do.experiment, append(unlist(vs), list(...)))
	metrics = mapply(metric, variables)
	data.frame(metrics)
}

series = function(..., range = 20:100, by = "n") {
	namedpair = function(value) {
		pair = c(value)
		names(pair) = by
		return(pair)
	}

	df = compare(..., variables = lapply(range, namedpair))
	colnames(df) = range
	return(df)
}

plot.series = function(series, title = "Power Functions") {
	matplot(colnames(series), t(series), type="l", main = title, lty=1)
	legend("topright", legend = rownames(series), col = 1:nrow(series), lty = 1)
}
In [ ]:
counts = function (sample, k) {
	as.numeric(table(cut(sample, seq(0, 1, length.out = k+1))))
}

pearson = function(sample, k) {
	N = counts(sample, k); np = length(sample)/k
	return( sum(((N - np)^2)/np) )
}

legpoly = function(sample, k) {
	# observation x polynomial
	polynomials = legendre.polynomials(n=k, normalized=TRUE)
	B = do.call(cbind, polynomial.values(polynomials=polynomials, 2*sample-1))
	B = sqrt(2)*B[, 2:ncol(B)]
	return(as.matrix(B))
}

neyman = function (sample, k) {
	B = legpoly(sample, k)
	n = length(sample)
	sum((colSums(B)^2)/n)
}

kolmogorov = function(sample) {
	G = ecdf(sample)
	sqrt(length(sample)) * max(abs(mapply(G, sample) - sample))
}

In [ ]:
identity = function(x, ...) x

do.experiment = function (times = 1e4, sampler = runif, n = 10, aggregate = identity) {
	sample = function(test, ...) {
		args = list(...)
		replicate(times, do.call(test, append(list(sampler(n)), args)))
	}

	P4 = aggregate(sample(pearson, k=4), q = qchisq(0.95, 3))
	P8 = aggregate(sample(pearson, k=8), q = qchisq(0.95, 7))
	N1 = aggregate(sample(neyman,  k=1), q = qchisq(0.95, 1))
	N4 = aggregate(sample(neyman,  k=4), q = qchisq(0.95, 4))
	N8 = aggregate(sample(neyman,  k=8), q = qchisq(0.95, 8))
	KS = aggregate(sample( kolmogorov ), q = sqrt(-log(0.05/2)/2))
	data.frame(P4, P8, N1, N4, N8, KS)
}

Excerise 2¶

The accept-reject von Neumann algorithm, is a simple method for generating random numbers from a desired probability distribution. Here's how it works:

Generate a candidate random number: Choose a random number from a known distribution that is easy to sample from.

Generate a uniform random number: Generate another random number uniformly between 0 and 1.

Accept or reject: If the uniform random number is less than the ratio of the desired probability distribution to the known distribution at the candidate value, accept the candidate; otherwise, reject it.

Repeat if rejected: If the candidate is rejected, go back to step 1 and try again.

Over time, the accepted candidates will converge toward the desired distribution. The efficiency of the algorithm depends on choosing a known distribution that is easy to sample from and closely approximates the desired distribution. It's an efficient way to leverage a simple, easily-sampled distribution to simulate more complex ones.

Exercise 3¶

In [ ]:
qC = function(j, p) function(u) 1 + p*cos(j*pi*u)

rC = function(n, j, p) {
	# accept-reject von Neumann algorithm
	M = 1 + p
	population = list()
	repeat {
		len = length(population)
		if (len == n) break
		x = runif(n - len)
		u = runif(n - len)
		population = append(population, x[u <= qC(j, p)(x) / M])
	}
	return(as.numeric(population))
}

In [ ]:
pwr = function(values, q) c(power = sum(values > q) / length(values))
C = function(j, p) function(n) rC(n, j, p)
In [ ]:
plot.series(series(times=1e3, aggregate=pwr, sampler=C(1, 0.4), range=seq(10, 100, 10)))

The probability of correctly rejecting the null hypothesis clearly increases with sample size and the convergence speed is greater for higher values of k.
